Meet the new champ, the newest member of the Human Disease Family

By Danni Peng

PUBLISHED: February 17,2020

On February 8, the National Health Commission announced that the COVID-19 pneumonia was temporarily named "COVID-19 pneumonia" , or "new crown pneumonia" , or "NCP" . The next day, in a new preprint paper, Zhong Nanshan et Al. dubbed the disease "acute respiratory disease of the 2019 COVID-19 infection (2019-cov ARD) " because not all infected people showed signs of pneumonia, the name refers to patients who test positive for the virus and have symptoms but no significant imaging findings.

Just as the understanding behind the name of the disease caused by the virus continues to refresh, the spread of the new crown disease has been more than a month, compared to the early days of the outbreak, in the process of treating patients, especially the critically ill patients, the medical staff participating in the first-line treatment gradually have a preliminary understanding of this brand-new infectious disease.

Debate over diagnostic criteria

On January 30, a patient attended the fever clinic of china-japan Friendship Hospital in Beijing. All the three throat swabs tested negative for novel coronavirus nucleic acid before admission, while positive for H1N1 nucleic acid. Because his pneumonia symptom is heavier at that time, so with"serious disease a current"admitted into hospital negative pressure single room ward, accept to have wound absorb support. However, during subsequent treatment, the patient was subjected to bronchoalveolar lavage and specimens were taken. On 5 February, nucleic acid tests showed that the patient was positive for the new coronavirus and was finally diagnosed.

Liang Lianchun, director of the General Department of infection at Beijing you 'an hospital, said in an interview with the Health newspaper that it is not uncommon for patients in Hubei Province to have multiple negative throat swabs and positive lower respiratory tract specimens. "If similar patients are admitted to a general ward, there will no doubt be very serious consequences, and in the case of hospitals, medical staff will be reduced due to isolation. "

The existence of "false negative" patients has brought challenges to the prompt treatment of the infected patients, the proper response and isolation measures of medical institutions and medical staff, the criteria for the diagnosis of NCP should be adjusted.

Aspiration and critical care expert Wang Chen, president of the Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences, said in an interview with CCTV on February 5 that the ability to detect viral nucleic acids is improving, but the accuracy of different reagents varies, not all patients test positive for nucleic acids. So there are a lot of patients with a history of exposure, clinical symptoms like that, but the nucleic acid hasn't been confirmed, and they're now classified as suspects. Wang Chen said, "I suggest that in Wuhan [ if ] there are such patients, they should be classified as clinical cases, because the positive rate of nucleic acid for confirmed patients is only between 30% and 50% , so it is very necessary to set up a clinical diagnostic grade. "

A microbiology expert, who did not want to be named, told China News weekly that the "false negative" nucleic acid test has reagent reasons, as well as sample reasons, there are individual differences, there are reasons for the characteristics of the virus itself. "sometimes it's really not the reagent, it's just not getting the sample, it's not getting good enough, it's taking too long for the sample to degrade and so on. "

Respiratory specimens including throat swab, nasopharyngeal swab, nasopharyngeal Swab, sputum, aspirate, bronchoalveolar lavage fluid, bronchoalveolar lavage fluid, etc. . At present, the nucleic acid detection of new coronary pneumonia mainly throat swabs, I. E. Pharyngeal Secretions. Because of the particularity of the new coronavirus, different sampling sites have great influence on the detection rate.

"because the lower respiratory tract contains more virus, the positive rate of lung sampling is higher, " Zhao Jianping, director of the aspiration and Critical Care Medicine Department at Tongji Hospital in Wuhan, told China News Weekly, however, this sampling method is not practical, so it is important to consider the patient's symptoms, chest imaging, and course of disease.

On Feb. 3, Zhang Xiaochun, deputy director of the imaging department at Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University, posted a message on his facebook page: "Don't be superstitious about nucleic acid detection. CT images are strongly recommended as the main evidence for 2019-nCoV pneumonia. " In response, several clinicians said, imaging can not replace the etiological examination, CT only suggests "possible" , the final diagnosis needs nucleic acid. Liu youning, a former chairman of the Chinese Medical Association's Internal Medicine Branch and head of the division of respiratory medicine at the 301 Military Hospital, wrote that CT was difficult to identify the causative agent, in particular, Adenovirus, mycoplasma pneumonia and other CT findings are very similar to COVID-19.

On Feb. 5, the COVID-19 released the fifth edition of its diagnosis and treatment plan for pneumonia in China, one of the most important changes to the plan is to separate Hubei Province from other provinces in terms of diagnostic classification criteria. In Hubei Province, the original "old three" , fever, leukopenia or lymphocyte, and CT images of the lungs, were split in two, so long as they met the first two criteria, they could be considered "suspected" , it's a relaxation of the rules of suspicion. But at the same time, the third lung CT performance as a "clinical diagnosis" for a new category of diagnosis in Hubei. That brings the debate over CT and the kit to a close.

Knowledge of disease reveals the tip of the iceberg

A number of complex new situations are challenging the existing understanding of NCP. For example, recent studies by Zhong Nanshan and others have found that the median incubation period for new pneumonia patients is three days, while individual cases have been found to be as long as 24 days. For example, on February 10, Guangxi and Henan reported two cases of asymptomatic infection, the asymptomatic presentation was 16 and 17 days, respectively.

A retrospective analysis of 138 NCP patients admitted to the central South Hospital of Wuhan University was carried out by Peng Zhiyong and others in the Department of Critical Care Medicine of the hospital, published in the well-known medical journal Jama on February 7, common symptoms included fever (98.6%) , fatigue (69.6%) and dry cough (59.4%) .

However, unlike people who use fever as the most obvious sign of infection, Zhong Nanshan et Al. report online Feb. 9 on Medrxiv, a preprint platform for medical research papers, a total of 1,099 patient samples from 552 hospitals in 31 provinces were analyzed as of January 29. It was found that only about 44% of patients had fever at the time of admission, at the early stage of infection with the new coronavirus, but 88% had fever after admission.

For critically ill patients, doctors have only a week or two to snatch a life. Based on a case study from Wuhan's Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome, Peng and others found that the average time from symptom onset to onset of dyspnea was six days, from admission to hospital was seven days, and from Acute respiratory distress syndrome to hospital was eight days.

Zhao Jianping, director of ICU at Wuhan Tongji Hospital, told viral pneumonia that compared with the past, patients with NCP started off very gently, and after a period of time, often after 7 to 10 days, some of them suddenly got worse, even two or three days could be life-threatening. Du Bin, Director of the Department of Internal Medicine in the Peking Union Medical College Hospital, also said that many cases in the early onset, only fever, weakness and other mild symptoms, but to the second week, 15% to 20% of patients with symptoms will suddenly become worse, symptoms such as respiratory failure.

Du estimated that the overall case fatality rate of the new severe pneumonia patients was 10% to 20% , and Huang Xiaobo, director of ICU of Sichuan Provincial People's Hospital, which took over the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, believed that the mortality rate of the severe cases was about 15%  Peng Zhiyong, director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University, calculated that the case fatality rate of critical cases was about 20% .

On the overall case fatality rate, Peng and his colleagues put the figure at 4.3 percent, based on the hospital's case study, and Zhong Nanshan and his colleagues put the case fatality rate at 1.36 percent, although the latter sample had a wider range of diagnoses, there were 483 residents in Wuhan, accounting for 44 percent of the total cases studied. As of February 6, more than 8,000 people had been confirmed outside Hubei, but 15 people had died, with a case fatality rate of 0.18 percent, especially in Zhejiang and Jiangsu provinces, where the number of cases reached nearly 1,000 but no deaths occurred, Liu said.

Zhao Jianping explained that the high case fatality rate in Wuhan is due to two factors: First, the virus is highly contagious and the number of infected people is growing rapidly, crowding out local medical resources, and some patients can not be hospitalized in time; second, there are no effective drugs to stop the progression from mild to severe illness.

In the case of specific drugs, early results have raised hopes for Gilead's antiviral drug, and other drugs, including traditional Chinese medicine, will require further clinical observation to determine their efficacy. Zhang Wenhong, director of the infection department of Mount Hua Hospital and head of the Shanghai Medical Treatment Expert Group, said in an interview that, "The most effective medicine is human immunity. What are we doctors doing? We're helping a patient get through two weeks, and when he gets through that, his own antibodies are up and he has a lot of power. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Peng Zhiyong also told China News weekly that the current treatment strategy for critically ill patients is to maintain, the most important thing is to ensure oxygen inhalation, which includes non-invasive and invasive breathing machines, and at the same time deal with the patient's multiple complications, to keep the organs functioning, the rest depends on the patient's immunity and strength. The virus is constantly replicating and attacking the immune system, so if a patient has a low lymphocyte, he has a low chance of survival.

However, immunity, the body's weapon against new coronaviruses, is also thought to cause attacks on itself. Li Wenliang, an ophthalmologist at Wuhan's Central Hospital, who attracted the attention of hundreds of millions of Internet users, died at the age of 34 after suffering from new coronary pneumonia. On January 31, China Newsweek also conducted an online interview with Li Wenliang, who was receiving treatment in the ICU. At that time, the doctor told him that the inflection point of the disease in these days, but it will take some time to recover lung function. But on the night of February 6, news of Li Wenliang's condition deteriorated and he died in the early hours of the next day.

This is not an isolated case of a young man in good health who suddenly becomes critically ill. One possible explanation offered by some experts is a "cytokine storm, " which suggests that young people have stronger immune systems and are more responsive to viral invasions, it then causes damage to multiple organs because of an overactive immune response. But Peng says this is just a theory.

Zhao Jianping told China News weekly that the virus had not been removed from the patient's body, so after a period of time the virus multiplied and then got worse. "Li Wenliang's situation at that time was definitely not much better and worse, but it was in a stalemate that was slightly more stable than before, with a slight easing for a while. "

"because we still do not know the pathogenesis of the new coronavirus, whether the multiple organ damage is caused by the virus itself or whether the virus invades the body and causes other bacteria to enter and present these complications is not known, and there is no specific medicine, " Du told the media, all of these bring great difficulties to the rescue and monitoring of the patients with severe disease, especially the critically ill patients with new pneumonia.

Re-understanding of transmission route

On February 5, the National Health Commission website published the diagnosis and treatment plan for COVID-19 pneumonia (trial version 5) , the description of the route of transmission of the virus is based on the description of "respiratory droplets and contact transmission are the main route of transmission" , and adds a new expression —— -- "the route of transmission such as Aerosol and alimentary tract remains to be defined" . Aerosol transmission refers to the mixing of droplets in the air, the formation of aerosols, inhalation leads to infection.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The SP-960 sample processing workstation built by Huada Zhizao is used for automated nucleic acid extraction in the automatic extraction room of the "Fireeye" laboratory in Wuhan, Donghu New Technology Development Zone, Feb. 6. Photograph by Zhou Chao, Changjiang daily

On February 8, the Shanghai Epidemic Prevention and Control Work Leading Group of the conference, health and epidemic prevention experts directly set the tone said that at present can determine the main route of transmission of new pneumonia is the direct transmission, aerosol transmission and contact transmission. The spread of aerosols means that viruses are in the air, so safe scenes of staying indoors or walking on empty roads can become dangerous.

Studies have shown that a sneeze produces between 400,000 and 200,000 droplets, compared with about 100,000 droplets produced by a single cough, and about 3,000 droplets produced by loud talking, with droplets ranging in size from 1 to 2,000 micrometres. "If we sneeze, there must be big particles and small particles, " a microbiology expert told China News Weekly. "Aerosols are small particles that can float in the air and are about 0.2 to 10 microns in size. "

During the SARS period, Amoy Gardens in Hong Kong had a concentrated outbreak of the epidemic situation. In Block E, 321 people were infected with the SARS virus and 42 died, which was considered to be the most likely transmission by Aerosol. Specifically: The virus-infected waste falls through hundreds of meters of sewage pipes and interacts with the air stream to form an atomization process, the droplets escaped through a crack in a pipe on the 8th floor and through unwatertight u-tubes in several homes, eventually evaporating and becoming a source of infection in the form of aerosols.

Related to this, the possibility of "faecal-oral transmission" was also of concern earlier due to the positive detection of viral nucleic acids in the stool of patients. On February 1, the Institute of Liver Disease at Shenzhen's COVID-19 found positive results in the stool of some patients with confirmed pneumonia, according to the COVID-19, this means that there may be a live virus in the stool of these patients.

The aforementioned microbiologist pointed out that coronaviruses replicate in the intestine, thus causing some symptoms such as diarrhea, so it is very possible that faeces can be used as a route of transmission, but how much role does it play in this virus, it's unclear at this time.

If a patient has a virus in his or her stool, it can form when he or she flushes the toilet, explains Bioaerosol, a professor at Southeast University's School of Energy and environment. These virus-carrying droplets, and evaporation of the formation of dry droplets of nuclear easily inhaled, or contact with the conjunctiva, Nasal Mucosa, oral Mucosa, it is possible to form infection. So far, however, the main evidence for faecal-oral infection has been limited to the discovery of new coronavirus nucleic acids in the faeces of a few patients, Liu said, which is far from conclusive. Faecal-oral transmission is unlikely to be the main route of transmission of the virus.

If an infected person sneezes, the virus can float around the park and infect people, which is not realistic, because infection requires certain conditions and amounts of the virus, the microbiology expert told China News Weekly. "Don't be afraid to hear about the spread of the Aerosol. There is no air without the virus. Even if there is a small amount of the virus in the air, it is safe. It is only possible to get infected if you stay in an environment with a high concentration of the virus for a certain period of time. "

On Feb. 9, Feng Ruzhao, a researcher with the Infectious Disease Division of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, answered that question. He said that the new crown pneumonia is still mainly through the droplet transmission and transmission of disease contact, in some special conditions may occur in aerosol transmission. He further explained that, "Aerosol transmission can only occur under certain conditions, such as during clinical procedures such as endotracheal intubation. If it is in routine clinical care, general working and living conditions, to take the right to wear masks of transmission of droplets, is sufficient to protect the general public from infection."

At this point, the so-called "Aerosol spread, " this in the current situation of the epidemic scare many people's problem, finally have a reassuring view.
